_source.content:
Fitzroy House by Manna Made

Transforming a single storey, semi-detached Victorian is a challenge Manna Made relish. They are always drawn to the innate charm and the opportunity to renew dark, narrow spaces into light-filled and generous environments. Fitzroy’s mix of terrace houses and industrial warehouses come together in this inner-city house. Choosing a monochromatic palette requires extra attention to be paid to the textures in a room.

Location: Fitzroy, VIC

Photo Credit: James Geer
_source.title: Fitzroy House

_source.content:
LlaneEast Reno by Homes by Ivy

Richly detailed and filled with light, Ivy fell in love with this unique renovators delight the moment she saw it. After an extensive renovation, it now offers all of the gracious conveniences of modern living inside a beautifully reinvigorated Edwardian cottage. A mix of original architecture, restored features and thoughtful interior design, the Llaneast House is full of stories to tell, new and old — but also with plenty of room for the new owners to make it tell their own.

Location: Armadale, VIC

Photo Credit: Dylan James

1940 Art Deco Armadale Apartment by Hunting for George

Lucy of Hunting for George updated this delightful art deco apartment in Melbourne. The Armadale apartment block is a favourite with locals. It was designed in the 1940s by Stuart Hall, and features Palm Springs-style landscaping and beautiful, curved architectural details.

Location: Armadale, VIC

Photo Credit: Nikole Ramsay

Upper Hastings Street Hong Henwood

This laidback designer home in Noosa is the holiday rental of our dreams, and was recently renovated by Hong Henwood Design. The modern coastal home takes inspiration from the Hamptons and tropical Singapore styles.

Location: Noosa, QLD

Photo Credit: Emma Bourne

_source.content:
Newtown Courtyard House by Built by Wilson

Lauren wanted to create the ultimate family home that allows connection and flow, but also has separate zones for living, work and kids. With so many people considering the move outside of Melbourne after COVID, Built by Wilson identified a gap in the market for beautiful family homes that are both functional and stylish. The internal courtyards tie the house together and the alfresco area with fireplace really completes the home.

Location: Newtown, VIC

Photo Credit: Dylan James

The New Canning by Josh and Jenna

Bayview House by The Northcote Stylist & BuildHer Collective

What was discovered about this house is that it had great bones, but it was a rabbit warren. Two kitchens, two living areas, a few bathrooms and a number of bedrooms - effectively two separate houses under the one roof. The Northcote Stylist and BuildHer had the opportunity to change the whole flow of the house, making it more functional for family style living with modern convenience, and was able to give it the love and polish it deserved!

Location: Melbourne, VIC

Photo Credit: Dylan James

The Cecil Street Project by Alison Lewis

Located in Melbourne’s leafy suburb of Kew, The Cecil Street Project was the previous home of Alison Lewis and her family. A renovator’s delight, Alison could see the huge potential this 1930’s Californian Bungalow had to offer. The home had a beautiful period style and wonderful bones, so the challenge was to turn this dark and pokey original home into the light-filled, open plan space it is now.

Location: Kew, VIC

Barefoot Bay Villa by The Designory

The Barefoot Bay Villa focuses on Australian coastal materiality and that touch of quintessential Byron effervescence. With strong contemporary finishes, luxe design elements and natural materials, the inspiration for the Bay Villa was drawn from the raw textures and tones of our breathtaking coastline – bush greens, rust, sandstone, sea foam, warm greys and sandy whites.

Location: Byron Bay, NSW

Fitzroy House by Manna Made

Transforming a single storey, semi-detached Victorian is a challenge Manna Made relish. They are always drawn to the innate charm and the opportunity to renew dark, narrow spaces into light-filled and generous environments. Fitzroy’s mix of terrace houses and industrial warehouses come together in this inner-city house. Choosing a monochromatic palette requires extra attention to be paid to the textures in a room.

Location: Fitzroy, VIC

Photo Credit: James Geer

_source.content:
Newtown Courtyard House by Built by Wilson

Lauren wanted to create the ultimate family home that allows connection and flow, but also has separate zones for living, work and kids. With so many people considering the move outside of Melbourne after COVID, Built by Wilson identified a gap in the market for beautiful family homes that are both functional and stylish. The internal courtyards tie the house together and the alfresco area with fireplace really completes the home.

Location: Newtown, VIC

Photo Credit: Dylan James

_source.content:
Bayview House by The Northcote Stylist & BuildHer Collective

What was discovered about this house is that it had great bones, but it was a rabbit warren. Two kitchens, two living areas, a few bathrooms and a number of bedrooms - effectively two separate houses under the one roof. The Northcote Stylist and BuildHer had the opportunity to change the whole flow of the house, making it more functional for family style living with modern convenience, and was able to give it the love and polish it deserved!

Location: Melbourne, VIC

Photo Credit: Dylan James

Fitzroy House by Manna Made

Transforming a single storey, semi-detached Victorian is a challenge Manna Made relish. They are always drawn to the innate charm and the opportunity to renew dark, narrow spaces into light-filled and generous environments. Fitzroy’s mix of terrace houses and industrial warehouses come together in this inner-city house. Choosing a monochromatic palette requires extra attention to be paid to the textures in a room.

Location: Fitzroy, VIC

Photo Credit: James Geer

_source.content:
Fitzroy House by Manna Made

Transforming a single storey, semi-detached Victorian is a challenge Manna Made relish. They are always drawn to the innate charm and the opportunity to renew dark, narrow spaces into light-filled and generous environments. Fitzroy’s mix of terrace houses and industrial warehouses come together in this inner-city house. Choosing a monochromatic palette requires extra attention to be paid to the textures in a room.

Location: Fitzroy, VIC

Photo Credit: James Geer

LlaneEast Reno by Homes by Ivy

Richly detailed and filled with light, Ivy fell in love with this unique renovators delight the moment she saw it. After an extensive renovation, it now offers all of the gracious conveniences of modern living inside a beautifully reinvigorated Edwardian cottage. A mix of original architecture, restored features and thoughtful interior design, the Llaneast House is full of stories to tell, new and old — but also with plenty of room for the new owners to make it tell their own.

Bayview House by The Northcote Stylist & BuildHer Collective

What was discovered about this house is that it had great bones, but it was a rabbit warren. Two kitchens, two living areas, a few bathrooms and a number of bedrooms - effectively two separate houses under the one roof. The Northcote Stylist and BuildHer had the opportunity to change the whole flow of the house, making it more functional for family style living with modern convenience, and was able to give it the love and polish it deserved!

Location: Melbourne, VIC

Photo Credit: Dylan James

Templestowe Townhouse 1 by Chamberlain Property

Townhouse 1 is light and airy, with crisp white walls, natural stone and hardwood finishes. One of the standout details is the curved bench seat in the kitchen, which is upholstered in a beautiful Warwick fabric. The luxurious textures of the terrazzo floor tiles, concrete basins and gunmetal tapware in the bathrooms are something to be desired.

Location: Templestowe, VIC

Photo Credit: Dylan James

The Cecil Street Project by Alison Lewis

Located in Melbourne’s leafy suburb of Kew, The Cecil Street Project was the previous home of Alison Lewis and her family. A renovator’s delight, Alison could see the huge potential this 1930’s Californian Bungalow had to offer. The home had a beautiful period style and wonderful bones, so the challenge was to turn this dark and pokey original home into the light-filled, open plan space it is now.

Location: Kew, VIC

Photo Credit: Dylan James

Three Gables by TrueBuild Homes and Kate Lawrence Interiors

Three Gables is a home balancing imperfect and natural finishes with sleek and refined elements. Hard surfaces such as concrete and timber are softened by tactile fabrics like our sheer linen curtains. Greys and neutrals add warmth to the black and white design. The balance of these contrasting materials and colours is what makes Three Gables stand out.

Location: Hawkesbury, NSW

Photo Credit: The Palm Co

_source.content:
Stanhope by Kincrest

The location needs no selling, it’s South Yarra. But even in this unsurpassed locale, Stanhope is ambitious. It’s new, it’s different and it’s creative. Simply put, Stanhope will be a timeless piece of Architecture. Externally it speaks to its surrounding context and turns the expansive landscape of trees and green spaces into the hero. Internally, world renowned Swedish designer Lotta Agaton drew inspiration from the Scandinavian light and minimalism. As an offering, Stanhope presents a beautifully considered place, sculptural in its presentation, sumptuous in its accommodation and utterly timeless in the legacy it was designed to create.

Location: South Yarra, VIC

Photo Credit: Emily Bartlett

Witta Circle by Hong Henwood, Shaun Lockyer and JW Constructions

Located in Noosa Heads on the Sunshine Coast, Witta Circle is a tropical sanctuary developed by renowned interior designer Hong Henwood, architect Shaun Lockyer and building team JW Constructions. The Cecil Street Project by Alison Lewis

Located in Melbourne’s leafy suburb of Kew, The Cecil Street Project was the previous home of Alison Lewis and her family. A renovator’s delight, Alison could see the huge potential this 1930’s Californian Bungalow had to offer. The home had a beautiful period style and wonderful bones, so the challenge was to turn this dark and pokey original home into the light-filled, open plan space it is now.

Location: Kew, VIC

Photo Credit: Dylan James

Lofty three-meter-high ceilings paired with skylights and an open plan living area instil a sense of sweeping space. With considerate design focus on creating easy flow through the home, the living area unfolds to an outdoor entertaining space and manicured garden.

_source.content:
Kingscliff by Kylie Camps

Custom-made, luxurious, and so very romantic, designer curtains are a magnificent addition to any space. With the ability to effortlessly elevate a room, curtains create texture, add to your colour palette, provide the ideal light throughout the day, and add privacy when required. Wistful, alluring and endearing – you simply cannot go wrong.

Photo Credit: Kylie Camps

Barefoot Bay Cottage by The Designory

_source.content:
Witta Circle by Hong Henwood, Shaun Lockyer and JW Constructions

Located in Noosa Heads on the Sunshine Coast, Witta Circle is a tropical sanctuary developed by renowned interior designer Hong Henwood, architect Shaun Lockyer and building team JW Constructions. Surrounded by water to the south and blending into the stunning landscape, this open plan, light-filled, airy property is like a modern oasis showcasing unique architecture, cascading greenery, natural tones, and minimal, yet delightful décor.

Location: Noosa Heads, QLD

Photo Credit: Brock Beazley

Arcos by Graya

Location: Paddington, QLD

Barefoot Bay Villa by The Designory

The Barefoot Bay Villa focuses on Australian coastal materiality and that touch of quintessential Byron effervescence. With strong contemporary finishes, luxe design elements and natural materials, the inspiration for the Bay Villa was drawn from the raw textures and tones of our breathtaking coastline – bush greens, rust, sandstone, sea foam, warm greys and sandy whites.

Location: Byron Bay, NSW

Photo Credit: Andy Macpherson and Cat Gerke

_source.content:
Stanhope by Kincrest

The location needs no selling, it’s South Yarra. But even in this unsurpassed locale, Stanhope is ambitious. It’s new, it’s different and it’s creative. Simply put, Stanhope will be a timeless piece of Architecture. Externally it speaks to its surrounding context and turns the expansive landscape of trees and green spaces into the hero. Internally, world renowned Swedish designer Lotta Agaton drew inspiration from the Scandinavian light and minimalism. As an offering, Stanhope presents a beautifully considered place, sculptural in its presentation, sumptuous in its accommodation and utterly timeless in the legacy it was designed to create.

Location: South Yarra, VIC

Photo Credit: Emily Bartlett

_source.content:
The Cecil Street Project by Alison Lewis

Located in Melbourne’s leafy suburb of Kew, The Cecil Street Project was the previous home of Alison Lewis and her family. A renovator’s delight, Alison could see the huge potential this 1930’s Californian Bungalow had to offer. The home had a beautiful period style and wonderful bones, so the challenge was to turn this dark and pokey original home into the light-filled, open plan space it is now.

Location: Kew, VIC

Photo Credit: Dylan James

_source.content:
Stanhope by Kincrest

The location needs no selling, it’s South Yarra. But even in this unsurpassed locale, Stanhope is ambitious. It’s new, it’s different and it’s creative. Simply put, Stanhope will be a timeless piece of Architecture. Externally it speaks to its surrounding context and turns the expansive landscape of trees and green spaces into the hero. Internally, world renowned Swedish designer Lotta Agaton drew inspiration from the Scandinavian light and minimalism. As an offering, Stanhope presents a beautifully considered place, sculptural in its presentation, sumptuous in its accommodation and utterly timeless in the legacy it was designed to create.

Location: South Yarra, VIC

Photo Credit: Emily Bartlett
